Here's an example of a JavaScript function that uses regular expressions to extract a three-character code from a filename in the format "57-1Jn.usfm":
```javascript
function extractCode(filename) {
  const regex = /(\d{2}-\w{3})\.usfm$/;
  const match = filename.match(regex);
  return match ? match[1] : null;
}
```
This function uses a regular expression pattern that matches the three-character code followed by a dot and the ".usfm" extension at the end of the filename. The parentheses around the matched group capture the code as a separate value, which is then returned by the function.
To use this function, you can pass in a filename as a string argument:
```javascript
const filename = "57-1Jn.usfm";
const code = extractCode(filename);
console.log(code); // Output: "1Jn"
```
This will extract the three-character code from the filename and store it in the `code` variable, which you can then use as needed. Note that this function assumes that the filename extension is always ".usfm", so you may need to modify it if your filenames have a different extension format.
